The RULES_PYTHON_REPO_TOOLCHAIN_<VER>_<OS>_<CPU> host-interpreter override
compares the env var's string against a list of (platform, meta) tuples, so
any preference fails with "Please choose a preferred interpreter out of the
following platforms" -- and had it passed, `candidates = [preference]` would
crash the later tuple unpack. Compare and filter by platform name instead.

The override is what lets the *-linux-musl release legs pick the musl
python-build-standalone interpreter: the default candidate order puts the
glibc build first, and a glibc interpreter does not run on Alpine.

--- a/python/private/toolchains_repo.bzl
+++ b/python/private/toolchains_repo.bzl
@@ -598,10 +598,10 @@
                 env_var,
                 candidates,
             ))
-        elif preference not in candidates:
+        elif preference not in [c[0] for c in candidates]:
             return logger.fail("Please choose a preferred interpreter out of the following platforms: {}".format(candidates))
         else:
-            candidates = [preference]
+            candidates = [c for c in candidates if c[0] == preference]
 
     if candidates:
         platform_name, meta = candidates[0]
